The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, April 02, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, April 1: The Reserve Bank of India today said the primary responsibility of complying with external commercial borrowing (ECB) guidelines wrests with the borrower and any contravention will be viewed seriously and may invite penal action. The designated authorised dealer was also required to ensure that raising or utilisation of ECB is in compliance with the guidelines at the time of certification, the RBI said today. On the end use of ECBs, it said the proceeds should not be used for working capital, general corporate purpose and repayment of existing rupee loans as per the revised norms.																								 Mumbai, April 1: Bharat Petroleum Corporation Ltd (BPCL) today announced a voluntary retirement scheme for eligible employees. The scheme would remain open till May 31.																								 Bangalore, April 1: Infosys Technologies Ltd will announce the results for its fourth quarter and financial year ended March 31, 2004 on April 12.																								 Mumbai, April 1: The Association of Mutual Funds in India (Amfi) will form a working group to explore prospects for mutual funds to invest in commodities futures and develop regulations for the same.																								 Mumbai, April 1: Tata Steel has crossed the 4-million-tonne mark in all categories of steel production in 2003-04, with saleable steel going up by 3.8 per cent to 4.09 million tonnes and crude steel to 4.22 MT.
